metadata.description:
V.Mountains is an abstract representation of the turbulence and chaos of our life.



The mountain is a symbol of the way that life is constantly in flux,

of the way that we are constantly trying to make sense of the world around us.



The mountain is a source of inspiration, a place of refuge, a source of strength.

It is a place where we can go to reflect on our lives, to find peace and solace.



The mountain is a symbol of hope.

It is a reminder that, no matter how dark and cold the world may be, there is always a chance for new beginnings.



The mountain is a symbol of the human spirit, and of our ability to persevere in the face of adversity.

It is a representation of our journey through life, with all of its ups and downs.

It is a reminder that, no matter how difficult the path may be,
we can always reach the summit if we are willing to put in the hard work.

We tend to forget that life finds its way and that we just need to hold enough to start to see a clear path to follow.

Life is momentary, the good times are momentary and of course the bad ones.

metadata.name: Mythic Latent Glitches  #20
metadata.description:
What is even real and what is artificial?

In the contemporary light, the division between real and artificial loses weight as the concepts become more and more intertwined. In this work, the artist combines the human and generative inputs, in a counterintuitive manner, by allowing AI to design the organic elements and using the human hand to incorporate artificial glitches. What seemingly emerges as natural forms, was imagined solely by GAN, seeing the world through the limited examples through the photographer‚Äôs lenses. Artist‚Äôs role is also reversed, as their goal is to design the visual destruction process of the organic forms. Glitch is a malfunction of perception, it symbolizes the confusion caused by not being able to comprehend. 

The human fascination with metaphysical forces spans many centuries. While Pagan mythology created gods living in deep forests and under-explored territories, nowadays we approach technology with somewhat similar awe, fascination, and fear. 

The project has been developed in multiple stages. It started with an inspiration by the Lithuanian landscape and research of the ancient myths and legends. The photography aimed at capturing the mysterious, spanning months and years of different experiences. A custom pre-trained artist‚Äôs GAN model was then trained on a collection of several hundred photographs in high resolution. Selected outputs were curated by artist and included as a starting canvas for the next stage. Then, a set of stochastic manipulations were programmed to create alternative narratives through the visual destruction. Fog turns into smoke into burning radioactive forest in an unpredictable manner, guided by the random variables, their boundaries crafted by artist.  

Read more on the project website:
ivonatau.com/mythic-latent-glitches

metadata.name: NAZCA #33
metadata.description:
Real time animation (WebGL)
Variable dimension
2022

Nazca is a group of living glyphs made in the soil of the GPU. There are 17 figures that get combined and mixed over three layers. The figures vary in complexity but are generally created with vertical and horizontal lines only. Figures have at least one seed, some even have a seed per path. A seed is an oscillating pixel that can be compared to a square wave oscillator of audio synthesis and is usually followed by a path or a set of paths. The purpose of the paths is to send the pixels along the lines to make the figures visible through movement and to create a reduction to pure animation.

metadata.name: Digital Surface 5 #4
metadata.description:
The mechanics of Digital Surface are inspired by nature and the aesthetics by pixels. Digital Surface is an attempt to find an autonomous visual logic for a digital world made by machines.
The image is created one pixel after another, calculating the proceeding pixel based on the previous generations.

Once the image is completed, press "s" to save in a small size, "m" in a medium, "l" in a large, "x" in a xlarge and "w" to save with the size of the window.

Digital Surface is a 5 series project. Each Series is released singularly, the fifth being Digital Surface 5. The main differentiations for series 5 are that each image contains 12 colors (accent colors and shades) and the pixel size is larger compared to the first 4 series. This is a special edition with colors inspired by videogames from the '90s.
This is Francesco Forcellini Studio's first NFT project broadening their field of work from physical to digital.

Built using p5js, published under CC-BY-NC-4.0 license.

Once the collection will be fully minted, the variations button will be disabled.

metadata.name: Boom_fx #123
metadata.description:
Boom_fx, by Stephen Boyd  
July, 2022  
Little India, Toronto, Canada.

Project Description
---
During the short history of fxhash, there have been several important dates marking the growth and evolution of the platform. Boom_fx is a visual interpretation of ten of these days through the lens of real world earthquake data and the colour palettes of Mark Rothko.

Each iteration of Boom_fx represents a window of time on one of these days and expresses the seismic activity that occurred.

These are creative interpretations and while the visual elements and relationships between objects are all based on detailed seismic data from the United States Geological Survey (USGS), they are not meant to be understood as maps.

The ten days were selected for having some significance to the growth and evolution of the fxhash platform and Tezos more broadly.

In chronological order:

1. September 2, 2014 - Tezos White paper released
2. June 30, 2018 - Tezos Initial Release
3. November 6, 2021- Genesis drop on fxhash
4. November 7, 2021 - ciphrd's and punevyr's first drops
5. November 11, 2021 - markknol drops 'SMOLSKULL'
6. December 9, 2021 - zancan drops 'Garden, Monoliths'
7. January 2, 2022 - E0 "The Genesis Drop" of Waiting to be Signed podcast'
8. March 31, 2022 - The Big Burn
9. April 16, 2022 - fxhash 1.0 release
10. March 27, 2022 - Opening day of Art Basel Hong Kong, 2022

There is an eleventh day included: July 18, 2022. This is the last full day of USGS Earthquake data before Boom_fx is published to fxhash.xyz. This date doesn't represent a milestone for the platform, it simply conveys a milestone for the work itself.

The earthquake data comes from the USGS API which very handily provides GeoJSON files. There is further documentation (./documentation/Information_about_boom_fx.md) included with this project that outlines how this data was collected and the information included in these feeds.

Features
--- 
1. Aspect ratios:
- Landscape 62% probability
- Portrait 24% probability
- Square 14% probability

2. Colour Palettes
Eleven Mark Rothko palettes. All equally probable.

3. Date
Each of the eleven days included in this project have an equal probability of being selected.

4. Concurrent minutes sampled during this day
There are six different durations used in this project and they all have an equal probability of being selected.

Interaction
---
Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press t: thumbnail @ a maximum pixel width or height of 200px
- Press s: your current screen size
- Press p: print size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 4800px which is 16"@300dpi
- Press h: HD4K on the vertical @ a maximum pixel width or height of 2160px
- Press m: Max size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 10800px. This is a biiiig size

The filename will include some metadata such as the unique hash, date and time at time of capture.

Data Sources, Software Libraries and VCS / Source Code
--- 

Data Sources
All earthquake data is sourced from the USGS Earthquake API for the International Federation of Digital Seismograph Networks (FDSN). Data was collected in GeoJSON format from the following endpoint: https://earthquake.usgs.gov/fdsnws/event/1/

Software Libraries Used
Made with Processing / P5.js  
p5.js v1.4.1 February 02, 2022

Version Control
https://github.com/sspboyd/boom
This repo is private as of July 2022. However, I have provided a source map with this project so please feel free to browse the code and see how it all works. There are a number of comments in the code explaining what is happening at different points.
